Part 1: Wrangling

Problem 1

Two tables were utilized: the Salaries table and Teams table. From the Salaries table, the year, team name, league, and calculated sum salary were obtained and from the Teams table, the games played, wins, losses, and calculated win percentage was obtained. An inner join was utilized so that rows across both tables were grouped together by matching year and team name. Rows were grouped by a common year and team name to view trends for teams by year

Inner join ensures that rows extracted from the Teams and Salaries table share a common year and team name. This means that any extraneous teams or years that are NOT found in both tables will not be included, which can useful for missing data.

Within the information collected, there was no missing data found. In the case of missing values, np.nan (NaN) would be used to replace any missing numerical values and 'None' would be used to replace any character values.

In [18]:
# The number of wins and games played must be casted to float in the calculation for 'Winning' or the resulting answer
# will be an integer
salary_query = "SELECT Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID, Salaries.lgID, sum(Salaries.salary) as total_payroll, \
Teams.G, Teams.W, Teams.L, CAST(Teams.W as FLOAT)/CAST(Teams.G as FLOAT)*100.0 as Winning \
FROM Salaries INNER JOIN Teams ON Salaries.yearID = Teams.yearID AND Salaries.teamID = Teams.teamID \
GROUP BY Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID"

A line graph was used to plot the data as the x-values are continuous and it's easy to view trends in payroll. For each unique team in the dataframe between the years 1990-2014, the yearID (x-values) and total_payroll (y-values) were obtained and converted to a list. Then they were both plotted onto the axis.

There are over 35 unique teams, so eventually the default colors used will loop over, causing duplicate line colors. To mitigate this, I created a list of patterns that would repeat a pattern every third iteration. This in turn triples the amount of unique line designs.

I created a separate function called plot_team for this. This reduced the amount of code required and reduces repetative code.

In [22]:
# list of patterns
patterns = ['dashed', 'dotted', 'dashdot']
# this function plots the payroll trends for a given team
def plot_team(team_name, index, ax):
    # obtain years for a given team
    x = (team_salaries[(team_salaries['teamID'] == team_name) & (team_salaries['yearID'] >= 1990)])['yearID'].tolist()
    # obtain total payroll for a given team
    y = (team_salaries[(team_salaries['teamID'] == team_name) & (team_salaries['yearID'] >= 1990)])['total_payroll'].tolist()
    # plot on axis
    ax.plot(x, y, linestyle = patterns[index], label=team_name)

Question 1

As time increases, the average payroll for each team drastically increases. Starting around 1990, the average payroll for each team was around $\$ 10,000,000 $. However, by 2014, the average payroll for most teams was at least $\$100,000,000$, 10 times greater. Along with an increase in the mean payroll per team, the spread of the payroll across teams increased as well. Looking at 1990, the lines of each team have a lot of overlap, indicating that the payroll for each team was fairly similar. However, by 2014, the lines for each team are at drastically different y-values, showing how vastly different the payroll was for each team.

Problem 3

There are two major values I want to plot: the mean payroll and standard deviation payroll for each year. This will help highlight the increase in payroll value and spread. I used a bar graph as it would allow me to use error bars to represent the standard deviation. Also, it provides visually distinct differences between mean payroll values. The black bars represent the standard deviation (+- 1 SD). I believe that this graph type would best represent the trends.

In [24]:
# clear axis to ensure that no extra data is being plotted
ax.clear()
# set initial year to 1990
year = 1990
# lists are used to collect the calculated standard deviation and average for each year
year_salaries_average_list = []
year_salaries_stdev_list = []
# used to collect years
year_list = []
while (year < 2015):
    # get values where 'yearID' equals 'year' and convert to list
    year_salaries = (team_salaries[team_salaries['yearID'] == year])['total_payroll'].tolist()
    # calculcate average
    average = sum(year_salaries)/len(year_salaries)
    # calculate mean using statistics module
    stdev = stat.stdev(year_salaries)
    # add values to appropriate lists
    year_list.append(year)
    year_salaries_average_list.append(average)
    year_salaries_stdev_list.append(stdev)
    # increment year by 1
    year = year + 1
# add bar graph for average salary and have error bars set to the standard deviation
ax.bar(year_list, year_salaries_average_list, yerr = year_salaries_stdev_list, label = 'Average')

ax.set_xlabel('Year', fontsize = 18)
ax.set_ylabel('Payroll ($ Hundred Million)', fontsize = 18)

A scatter plot was used to display the values from each time period. From there a line of best was generated to see if there was a trend.

Since different values are being plotted for each axis, one issue that can arise is that the range of the x-values and y-values on the axes can vary, resulting in misleading comparisons. To prevent this, sharey and sharex are both set to True so that each axes of the figure is the same. One consequence of this however, is that for some of the plots, the datapoints will be squished together.

For each of the scatter plots, I also calculated the r value to quantify how strong the correlation was between the two variables. A value closer to 1 indicates a strong positive direct relationship.

In [26]:
# use pandas.cut to split into 5 bins 
team_salaries['yearBins'] = pd.cut(team_salaries['yearID'], bins=[1989, 1994, 1999, 2004, 2009, 2014])
# create figure and axes
fig_cut, ax_cut = plt.subplots(5, figsize=(10, 50), sharey = True, sharex = True)
# set initial year to 1989
year = 1989.0
# i used to iterate through axes
i = 0
while year < 2014.0:
    # clear axis to make sure no extra values are included
    ax_cut[i].clear()
    # store mean values of win percentage and payroll for each time period
    average_payroll_list = []
    average_win_list = []
    # isolate rows where it has the matching Interval (i.e. time period) year is not inclusive
    isolated_df = team_salaries[team_salaries['yearBins'] == pd.Interval(year, year+5, closed = 'right')]
    for team in isolated_df.teamID.unique():
        # calculate mean winning percentage and payroll for each unique team in time period 
        isolated_team_df = isolated_df[isolated_df['teamID'] == team]
        average_payroll = isolated_team_df['total_payroll'].mean()
        average_win = isolated_team_df['Winning'].mean()
        # plot and add labels
        col, mark = get_plot_design(team)
        ax_cut[i].scatter(average_payroll, average_win, label=team, marker=mark, color = col)
        ax_cut[i].set_title("Average Winning Percentage vs. Average Payroll for Each Team Between the Years " + str(year+1.0) + " and " + str(year+5.0) +" (Inclusive)", fontsize = 18)
        ax_cut[i].set_ylabel("Average Winning Percentage (%)", fontsize=18)
        ax_cut[i].set_xlabel("Average Payroll ($ Hundred Million)", fontsize=18)
        ax_cut[i].legend(prop={'size': 8})
        # only label 'OAK' or 'MIN' points as this is the main focus of the project
        # 'MIN' is used for the next question which is why I labeled it
        if (team == 'OAK' or team == 'MIN'):
            ax_cut[i].annotate(team, (average_payroll, average_win))
        # append values to list
        average_payroll_list.append(average_payroll)
        average_win_list.append(average_win)
    # generate line of best fit for each axis and plot
    m, b = np.polyfit(average_payroll_list, average_win_list, 1)
    a = np.asarray(average_payroll_list)
    ax_cut[i].plot(a, m*a + b)
    # calculate r value
    r = np.corrcoef(average_payroll_list, average_win_list)[0][1]
    print("The r value between the years " + str(year+1) + " and " + str(year+5) + " is " + str(r))
    # increment year by 5 and index by 1
    year += 5.0
    i += 1

Question 2

There is overall a weak/moderate direct correlation between winning percentage and team payroll. The r values range from 0.3 to 0.7, supporting this claim. The plot with the strongest correlation is between 1995 and 1999.

A team with good spending efficiency will have a low payroll but high winning percentage, meaning they will be located at the top left of the plot. There are some teams that are overall good at spending such as 'MIN' who are almost consistetly have a high winning percentage using a low amount of payroll. However, out of all of the teams, 'OAK' had the best spending, with its most efficient spending occurring between the years 2000-2005. One can observe this from the fact that the point is in the top left of the plot.

The trends outlined in the project are reflected in the plots. Before 2000, OAK had an average efficiency (the OAK points are near the linear regression line). During 2000-2005, the efficiency was way above average. Following this, more teams experienced increased effiency (more points near the top left of the plot).

Part 3: Data Transformation

Problem 5

For a more accurate comparison between payroll between years, a standard payroll column was created. This is calculated by taking the payroll, subtracting by the average, and then dividing by the standard deviation. This is like calculating a z-score and provides a relative comparison between different payrolls.

In [27]:
# used to access averages and SDs from the lists created from the previous problem
index = 0
# set initial value to NaN
team_salaries['standard_payroll'] = np.nan
# 25 is the last entry since there are 25 years
while index < 25:
    # lambda function used to calculate standardized value
    team_salaries['standard_payroll']=team_salaries.apply(lambda x: (x.total_payroll - year_salaries_average_list[index])/year_salaries_stdev_list[index] if x.yearID == year_list[index] else x.standard_payroll, axis = 1)
    # increment axis
    index = index + 1

Question 4

Unlike the plots for question 2 and 3 where the data was broken into time periods of 5 years, this plot shows exact years where each team has good efficiency. Regions where the efficiency is greater than 0 are considered period of good efficiency. Although this efficiency can be observed in the plots for question 2 and 3 by observing the distance between the linear regression line and point on the plot, this plot quantifies that difference and visualizes it in on a graph. This number reflects the effectiveness of their strategy. They were able to achieve an above average winning record while spending relatively little on their payroll.

As previousley stated, the plots from question 2 and 3 show that spending more money can generally lead to increased winning. However, it's not guranteed. Teams like Oakland were able to spend money more efficiently, leading to outstanding results. To get a more clear understanding of the data, a more detailed breakdown of the spending is required.

# establish a HTTP request for the webstie containing the salary tables
menu = requests.get('http://www.stevetheump.com/Payrolls.htm')
# convert to BeautifulSoup object and look for table element
soup = BeautifulSoup(menu.text, features="lxml")
table = soup.find_all('table')

This provides the tables of salaries for each of the years. Index 2 is the year 2020 and each increment represents one year less. So for example, index 3 is the year 2019. Since each table is formatted differently, the parsing required is different for each one.

In [39]:
# for 2020
# master_list is the list of each row of the salaries dataframe
master_list = []
# row represents one row
row = []
temp = table[2].text.split('\n')
temp = list(filter(None, temp))
for i in range(len(temp)):
    # conditions are used to determine if its total payroll column
    # i - 4 is the # column, just used to make sure that total payroll column is being used
    if '$' in temp[i] and temp[i-4] == '30':
        row.append(2020)
        # i-5 is team name
        row.append(temp[i-5])
        # do not want $ or , when casting
        row.append(float(temp[i][1:len(temp[i]) -1].replace(',', '')))
        master_list.append(row)
        row = []

        row.append(float(temp[i][1:len(temp[i]) -1].replace(',', '')) + float(temp[i+1][1:len(temp[i+1]) -1].replace(',', '')))
        master_list.append(row)
        row = []
